## 1. Purpose
This policy defines how [COMPANY] uses artificial-intelligence systems — third-party generative-AI tools used by the workforce and AI/LLM features built into the product — without exposing PHI, Confidential data, or intellectual property, and without delegating consequential decisions to unaccountable automation. It turns the Acceptable Use Policy's prohibition on unapproved AI tools into a managed, auditable capability: approved tools, contractual guardrails, data rules, and secure engineering requirements.

## 2. Scope
Applies to all workforce members and contractors, and to: external AI services and assistants ([ChatGPT], [Claude], [Copilot], code assistants, transcription/meeting tools), AI capabilities embedded in approved SaaS, models and AI services used inside the product ([AWS Bedrock], [Snowflake Cortex], hosted or self-hosted models), and the data pipelines that feed them. It covers use with any [COMPANY] data classification, with PHI receiving the strictest treatment.

## 3. Policy
1. Workforce members **shall** use only AI tools listed in the **Approved AI Tools register** (§5); any other AI tool **shall not** receive [COMPANY] data of any classification above Public.
2. **PHI shall not be provided to any AI service without** (a) an executed BAA covering the AI processing, (b) contractual terms prohibiting training/retention on [COMPANY] data, and (c) approval recorded in §5 — all three, before first use (`../vendor/third-party-risk-management-policy.md.template`).
3. Data supplied to AI systems **shall** follow the data rules in §6, applying **minimum necessary** (`../healthcare/minimum-necessary-standard.md.template`) and preferring de-identified data (`../healthcare/de-identification-and-limited-data-set.md.template`) wherever the purpose permits.
4. AI output that informs **consequential decisions** (clinical, coverage, employment, security response) **shall** be reviewed by an accountable human before action; AI **shall not** be the sole basis for such decisions.
5. AI-generated code **shall** pass the same review, testing, and scanning gates as human-written code (`secure-sdlc-policy.md.template`); AI-generated content **shall** be reviewed for accuracy, licensing, and data leakage before external use.
6. AI features in the product **shall** go through threat modeling that explicitly covers AI-specific risks — prompt injection, data exfiltration via model output, training-data poisoning, excessive agency of tool-using agents — per `secure-sdlc-policy.md.template`.
7. Secrets, credentials, and keys **shall not** be provided to AI tools; AI systems **shall** authenticate to [COMPANY] resources with least-privilege, dedicated identities (`../access/access-control-policy.md.template`).
8. Prompts and outputs of product AI features that can touch PHI **shall** be logged per `logging-and-monitoring-policy.md.template`, with logs protected to the same standard as the data class involved.
9. Every AI system in use **shall** be recorded in the Approved AI Tools register with its data ceiling, contractual basis, and owner; the register is reviewed at least [quarterly].

## 4. Roles & Responsibilities
| Role | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| [Security Officer / CISO] | Owns this policy and the Approved AI Tools register; evaluates and approves tools; monitors compliance. |
| [Privacy Officer] | Confirms BAA/no-training terms and minimum-necessary compliance for any PHI-adjacent AI use. |
| [Engineering Lead] | Ensures AI features meet SSDLC/threat-modeling requirements; owns product AI system entries. |
| Managers | Route AI tool requests through the approval process; prevent shadow-AI adoption in their teams. |
| All Workforce / Contractors | Use only approved tools within their data ceiling; report accidental exposure immediately. |

See `../governance/roles-and-responsibilities.md.template` for full role definitions.

