## 6. Data Rules by Classification
<!-- TEMPLATE: Align tiers with data-classification-and-handling.md.template. -->

| Classification | Rule for AI use |
|---|---|
| Public | Any approved tool. |
| Internal | Approved tools with enterprise/no-training terms. |
| Confidential (incl. source code) | Approved tools with no-training terms and access controls; no secrets or credentials ever. |
| PHI / Restricted | Only tools meeting **all** §3.2 conditions (BAA + no-training + recorded approval); minimum necessary applied; de-identify where the purpose permits. |

## 7. Incident Handling
Suspected or actual exposure of PHI or Confidential data to an unapproved AI tool **shall** be reported immediately per `../resilience/incident-response-plan.md.template` and assessed for breach-notification obligations per `../healthcare/hipaa-breach-notification-procedure.md.template`. Prompt-injection or model-abuse findings in product features are handled as security incidents.

## 8. Exceptions
Exceptions (e.g., a pilot of a new AI tool) require documented risk acceptance per `../governance/exceptions-and-waivers.md.template`, approved by the [Security Officer], time-bound, and recorded in the exceptions log. The §3.2 PHI conditions are **not** waivable (POL-GOV-11 §6).

## 9. Compliance, Monitoring & Enforcement
Compliance is monitored through the Approved AI Tools register review, [DLP/egress monitoring or browser controls] where deployed, SSDLC gate evidence for product AI features, and workforce acknowledgment via the AUP. Violations are handled per `../people/hr-security-policy.md.template`; PHI mishandling follows `../healthcare/sanctions-policy.md.template`.

